ode—'migration applied twice by accident due to race condition'—requires actual separate processes competing for the same database resource.","test_description":"Spawn two independent Node.js processes, each running the migration runner against the same test PostgreSQL database with identical migration files. Coordinate their startup to begin at approximately the same time. Let both run to completion and verify: (a) no application error or database corruption occurs, (b) each migration file is applied exactly once (inspect _migrations table—no duplicate entries), (c) the final database state is correct and consistent.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.6,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The initialization sequence—'does _migrations table get created before migrations run?'—can be partially tested at Unit level with mocking (mock the query to return 'table not found', verify CREATE TABLE is called). However, Integration testing with a real empty database is more reliable because it verifies the actual DDL succeeds and the table is properly initialized in the real PostgreSQL, preventing bugs where the CREATE TABLE statement fails or the table schema is wrong.","test_description":"Start with a fresh test database that contains no tables (or drop the _migrations table if it exists). Run the migration runner. Verify: (a) the _migrations table is created with the correct schema, (b) the table is created before any migration files are applied (check _migrations metadata to confirm it was the first operation), (c) migrations are successfully applied after the table creation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reas